===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|penne|penne|enclosure for animals|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|penn|penn|enclosure, fold, pen|lang=ang}} (in compounds), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|pennō|lang=gem-pro}}, {{recons|pannijō||pin, bolt, nail, tack|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|bend-||pointed peg, nail, edge|lang=ine-pro}}. Akin to {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|pennian|pennian|to close, lock, bolt|lang=ang}} (in compounds {{term|onpennian|onpennian|to open|lang=ang}}), {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|pennen|pennen|to secure a door with a bolt|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|pinn|pinn|peg, bolt|lang=ang}}. More at {{l|en|pin}}.

Sense “prison” originally figurative extension to enclosure for persons (1845), later influenced by {{term|penitentiary||prison|lang=en}}, being analyzed as an abbreviation (1884).<ref name="oetyld">{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# An [[enclose]]d area used to contain [[domesticated]] animals, especially [[sheep]] or [[cattle]].
#: ''There are two steers in the third '''pen'''.''
# A place to confine a person; a prison cell.
#: ''They caught him with a stolen horse, and he wound up in the '''pen''' again.''
# {{baseball}} The [[bullpen]].
#: ''Two righties are up in the '''pen'''.''

