===Etymology 2===
[[Image:Ballpoint-pen-parts.jpg|thumb|right|A ballpoint pen, showing assembly.]]
{{etyl|xno}} {{term|penne|lang=xno}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|penne|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|penna||feather|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|petna-|lang=ine-pro}}, from {{proto|ine-pro|title=|pet-|to rush, fly}} (from which {{term|petition|lang=en}}). Proto-Indo-European base also root of {{proto|ine-pro|title=|petra-}}, from which {{term|πτερόν||wing|tr=pteron|lang=grc}} (whence {{term|pterodactyl}}), Sanskrit {{term|patram||wing, feather|lang=sa}}, Old Church Slavonic {{term|pero||pen|lang=cu}}, Old Norse {{term|fjöðr|lang=non}}, Old English {{term|feðer|lang=ang}} (Modern English {{term|feather|lang=en}});<ref name="oetyld"/> note the /p/ → /f/ Germanic sound change.

See {{term|feather|lang=en}} and {{term|πέτομαι|lang=grc}} for more.

